##The New England Journal of Medicine: anti-aids drugs fail to shorten the time it takes for new patients to improve

The results of the world's first randomized controlled clinical trial of COVID-19 pneumonia were published online March 19 in the The New England Journal of Medicine, a collaboration between Beijing's china-japan Hospital and Wuhan's Jinyintan Hospital.

The aim of this clinical trial was to investigate the efficacy of Lopinavir Ritonavir in the treatment of severe new coronary pneumonia (COVID-19) . This is also the first time since the new coronavirus outbreak that the world's top medical journal has published the results of a clinical trial for the treatment of new coronavirus pneumonia, clinical trials at a time of such difficult outbreaks are heroic.

This clinical Trial was abbreviated to Lotus China Lopinavir Trial for Suppression of SARS-Cov-2 in China by Professor Cao Bin, Director of sino-japanese Friendship Hospital, Dingyu Zhang, and academician Chinese Academy of Engineering Wang Chen. The Lead Author, Dr Capital University of Medical Sciences, from the Department of Respiratory Medicine of Japan, and Fan Guohui, from the Institute of Clinical Medicine of China and Japan.

According to Cao Bin, when he was treated at Golden Pond Hospital in early January, he first thought of Favipiravir as a candidate, and then screened out Lopinavir, Ritonavir, and Radzivir, because of clinical accessibility issues (Favipiravir and Ridgeville were not available in China at the time) , the first clinical trial was conducted with Ropinavir and Ritonavir.

Lopinavir Ritonavir is an old aids drug that was first identified as "potentially effective" after the outbreak of the new coronavirus.

However, the results of the study showed that no benefit was observed in severe COVID-19 adult inpatients treated with Lopinavir / Ritonavir compared with conventional therapy, primarily as compared with conventional support alone, there was no clinical improvement or reduction in mortality with the addition of Lopinavir and Ritonavir on the basis of conventional therapy. But in a number of secondary clinical indicators, as well as in an improved intention to treat analysis, patients using Ritonavir showed clinical benefits.

As early as Feb. 22, the Shanghai Public Health Center also published a study that did not find the effect of cleats / abidore on the treatment of new coronary pneumonia, but also said at the time that the efficacy of the study is doubtful.

A total of 199 patients with laboratory-confirmed SARS-CoV-2 infection were included in the trial, which was carried out in collaboration between Beijing China-japan Hospital and Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital. ninety-nine patients were randomly assigned to the Lopinavir / Ritonavir Group, 100 patients were assigned to the Conventional Treatment Group, and patients in the Lopinavir / Litteau group received Lopinavir / Ritonavir (400 mg / 100 MG) twice daily for 14 days. Because there was no time to prepare a placebo, the team said, the trial was not double-blind.

The median age was 58 years and 60.3% of the patients were male. The median time between symptom onset and random grouping was 13 days, with no significant differences in demographics, baseline laboratory findings, rating scale score distribution, or NEWS2 score at group entry. During the trial, 33.0% of patients in the GLUCOCORTICOID Litteau group and 35.7% of patients in the conventional therapy group received systemic glucocorticoid therapy.

The primary end point of the trial was the time to clinical improvement, when patients were assigned to a 7-point scale, patients were observed from the time of randomization to the time of improvement of the scale score by 2 points, or to the time of discharge (whichever occurred first) .

The 7-point scale includes: 1. Not Hospitalized, and can continue to engage in daily activities; 2. Not Hospitalized but unable to continue daily activities; 3. Hospitalization without oxygen. 4. Hospitalization, need oxygen; 5. Hospitalization requires Nasal high-flow oxygen therapy, noninvasive mechanical ventilation, or both; 6. Hospitalization requires ECMO, invasive mechanical ventilation, or both; 7. Death. This is the end point recommended by the WHO'S R & D Blueprint Expert Group.

Other clinical outcomes include, clinical status, 28-day mortality, duration of mechanical ventilation, length of hospital stay of survivors and time from the beginning of treatment to death were assessed using a 7-point scale on days 7 and 14. Virological parameters included the proportion of patients with viral RNA detected over time and the area under the viral RNA titer curve (AUC) .

Since the 3 patients died within 24 hours of Randomization, the attending physicians of the 2 patients refused to prescribe Lopinavir Litteau, in fact 94 patients received Lopinavir Ritonavir.

The results showed that there was no difference in the primary end point, the time of clinical improvement, between the Lopinavir and Ritonavir treatment and the conventional treatment. The 28-day mortality rate was similar in the Lopinavir / Litteau group and the Conventional Treatment Group (19.2% vs. 25.0%) . The percentage of patients with detectable viral RNA at each point in time was similar between the two groups.

In a modified intention-to-treat analysis that excluded 3 early-death patients, the median time between the two groups to clinical improvement (15 days vs 16 days) was statistically significant, although the difference was small.

In addition, a subgroup analysis found that the median time to rapid recovery from clinical conditions for patients treated within 12 days of symptom onset was 16.0 days for the Lopinavir Ritonavir Treatment, compared with 17.0 days for the conventional treatment, the mortality rate was 19.0% , which was lower than 27.1% in routine treatment.

But none of the subgroups treated 12 days after the onset of symptoms were found to have this condition.

According to the team, this suggests that whether there is a clinical benefit to treating COVID-19 with lopinavir-Litteau early is an important question for further study. This observation is consistent with studies showing that SARS-CoV-2 viral pneumonia in the second week of onset, and with the onset time previously observed in antiviral studies of SARS and severe influenza.

In addition, the number of patients receiving Lopinavir Ritonavir who developed severe complications (acute kidney injury and secondary infection) or required noninvasive or invasive mechanical ventilation due to respiratory failure, fewer than patients who did not receive Lopinavir or Ritonavir.

Cao Bin says that in the face of a new outbreak of respiratory infections, it is difficult to identify and treat drugs quickly and effectively. Previous studies of Ritonavir, Ribavirin and interferon have been inconclusive, from SARS in 2003 to Mers in Saudi Arabia in 2012, successive missed opportunities to explore a treatment for coronaviruses contributed to the antiviral drug of the COVID-19 pandemic. The results of this study are not only relatively clear that Ritonavir has some clinical benefits for severe COVID-19, but also provide valuable experience for the future exploration of effective antiviral drug.
